{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_frederick_ver03/data/sn89060127/00279522023/1937120301/0559.xml":{"full_text":"Page 6\nWORCESTER DEMOCRAT\nAND\nTHE LEDGER-ENTERPRISE\nPublished Every Friday at Pocomoke City, Maryland.\nEDWARD J. CLARKE, Editor and Owner\n$1.60 The Year In Advance.\nEntered at the Postoffice at Pocomoke City, Maryland, as Second Class Matter\n\u00a33b Mn NATIONAL EDITORIAL\nASSOCIATION\nFRIDAY, DECEMBER 3,1937\nA FORECAST\nMost of Washington\u2019s best guessers are willing to bet that the\nspecial session of Congress will adjourn without having passed a\nsingle major law. The one possible exception is that it may make\nsome extremely necessary changes in taxes.\nThere are many contributing reasons for that forecast, but\nthe biggest is that basic human emotion\u2014fear.\nWhen the last session ended, Congressmen were supposed to\ngo back home and get the \u201cfeel\u201d of the country. Then they were\nto be summoned into special session to finish up the legislative\nprogram laid out for them last January.\nThey did go home and they did get the feel. But the ef\nfect was just the oposite of what had been hoped. It strengthened\nrather than weakened the tentative convictions of many members\nthat they had been playing with dynamfte by approving economic\nexperiments which few people understood.\nAccording to their stories, the biggest thing the Congressmen\nfound \u201cback home\u201d was a surprising lack of real optimism. Then,\njust before they headed Washingtonward, the business recession\nbegan to make itself felt.\nWith individual optimism missing and with businesses forbid\nden by taxes to build up reserves to carry them through a reces\nsion, it is only natural that the legislators should wonder. Now,\nfor the first time in years, they are dubious about such things as\nthe wage-hour bill, the \u201clittle TVA\u2019s,\u201d lump sum appropriations,\nand giving the President virtually unlimited power to reorganize\nthe federal government.\nRegardless of what else might' be said about these things, they\ndo not stimulate confidence because all of them are experiments\nand nobody knows for sure what they will do.\nOpening day of any legislative session is just another day to a\nlot of Congressmen. They know it takes about a week to get the\nCongressional machinery into operation, so many of the old-timers\n\u2014unless they hold positions of leadership or committee chairman\nships which demand that they be present\u2014deliberately avoid the\nhullabaloo of opening day.\nThat was as true for the special session as ever. The galler\nies were packed with spectators, but there were empty seats on\nthe floors of both House and Senate.\nInterestingly, though, the greetings exchanged by members in\nthe cloakrooms and lobbies were less effusive and the talk about\nlegislation was more serious.\nIllustrative of the changing Washington viewpoint was a con\nference the other day among some high-ranking office holders.\nThey got around to a discussion of the business recession, and the\nhigh spot was reached when one \u201cadvanced thinker\u201d suggested\nflatly that the situation showed the weaknesses of a democratic\nform of government. He wondered whether socialism wouldn\u2019t be\nthe answer\u2014govrnment ownership and operation of all business\nand industry.\nHe got landed on like the proverbial ton of brick. His two\nmost bitter critics were men who said only a year ago that our sys\ntem was a bad one.\nRAILROADS AND NEWSPAPERS\nThe railroad industry has applied for permission to raise\nfreight rates 15 per cent, because its revenues are not sufficient in\nthese days of high costs and wages to pay expenses and leaves an\nadequate amount over for improvement and expansion.\nIn asking this permission, the railroads want to do only what\nmost unregulated businesses have already done. For example,\nnewspapers all over the country have been increasing thir single i\ncopy prices and in some cases their monthly or annual subscrip\ntion prices. Increased production costs makes this necessary.\nThe railroads are in the same position as these papers. Every\nthing the lines use costs more than it did a year or two ago, even as\na newspaper\u2019s main source of expense, newsprint, costs more than\nit did. And, like the newspapers, the railroads\u2019 only source of op\nerating income is from the sale of their services\u2014in one case,\ntransportation; in the other, advertising and news.\nWhenever a regulated industry asks permission for rate in\nceases the average human reaction is to protest at once, and hope 1\nthat it will be denied. But a railroad isn\u2019t any different from a\nnewspaper or a real estate agency or a grocery store or a specialty\nshop. It is governed by the same economic laws. And when out\ngo exceeds income, it must raise its prices or go bankrupt.\nCONTROLLING DANGEROUS FORCES\nAs Albert W. Whitney of the National Conservation Bureau\nand the National Safety Council, points out, civilization is constant\nly introducing new hazards into life, such as steam, electricity, ex\nplosives, poisons, locomotives and airplanes. Gradually, as our\nknowledge increases, we learn how to use such new forces and de\nvices so that they may perform the utmost in public service with\na minimum of risk.\nThe automobile is in the same category. And it can be dealt\nwith in the same manner as other dangerous forces whose menaces\nhave been eliminated or greatly subdued, and whose contributions\nto better living and working conditions have been correspondingly\nincreased.\nEducation is the essential thing. And it must not be hit-and\nmiss education. It must represent a permanent, planned program,\nadministered by experts.\n1 So far as the traffic problem is involved, it is difficult to edu\ncate the adult. But the adults of tomorrow can be taught to use\nour sreets and highways carefully and properly. Amazing pro\ngress has been made in expanding safety education and training\nin school curriculums. Students are not only taught the rudiments\nof safe driving, but what is equally important, the rudiments of\nsafe walking. The result is found in the statistics\u2014a steady de\ncline in traffic fatalities to children of school age, even though fa\ntalities to adults greatly increased during the same years.\nThe school which does not teach safety shirks its responsibili\nty to the children in its care, and to the community at large. Com\nparatively little expense is required to adopt and carry on a safety\ncourse\u2014and the saving, measured in dollars as well as in the more\nimportant coin of lives, is incalculably greater.\nON THANKSGIVING\nAmericans in any walk of life can look about them and reflect\nthat they indeed have considerably more to be thankful for than\nour pioneer forefathers, who, 316 years ago, paused in their No\nvember labors to toast their first harvest on American soil \u2014the\nfirst Thanksgiving Day.\nWe see about us the harvest of our own labors\u2014a harvest\ngiving greater comfort and greater security; comforts which those\nWORCESTER DEMOCRAT, POCOMOKE CITY, MARYLAND\npioneers never dreamed would exist; machines doing the back\nbreaking labor of the harvest; man, the master of the machine,\nwhether that machine be an automobile, radio, electric washing\nmachine, tractor or steam turbine\u2014a greater harvest produced by\na great deal less effort than our forefathers found necessary.\nWe feel about us a wealth of intangibles for which we also\ngive thanks: an inalienable freedom to worship in the house of our\nchosen faith, to speak without fear or reprisal, the right of unham\npered enterprise and freedom from political dominance; our chil\nden receiving more education and more opportunity than exists any\nplace else in the world. We are thankful that we live in America,\na nation blessed with Constitutional liberty for the individual and\na constantly rising living standard.\nMr. James Jones\nWeds Mrs. L. Marshall\nA very simple but pretty wedding\nwas solemnized at the Baptist Church\non Wednesday evening, November 24,\nwhen Mrs. Louella Jones Marshall, of\nFederalsburg, formerly of near Poco\nmoke, became he bride of Mr. James\nS. Jones, of Baltimore.\nThe altar was beautifully and taste\nfully decorated with evergreens and\nchrysanthemums. The ceremony was\nperformed by the Rev. John A. Ditto\nwith Mrs. Grady A. Powell at the or\ngan.\nThe only atendants were Mr. and\nMrs. Nicholas M. D\u2019Addaire, of Ger\nmantown, Pa. Mrs. D\u2019Addardie was\nformerly Miss Lillian Townsend of\nthis city, a life long friend of the\nbride.\nThe bride wore a tailored suit of\nnavy blue with a corsage of bride\u2019s\nroses. Mrs. D\u2019Addarie wore black vel\nvet with talisman roses.\nAfter a short honeymoon the happy\ncouple will be at home in Federals\nburg, Maryland.\nCHIRPS\nContinued from Page 1\nEastern Sho\u2019, now and forevermo\u2019,\nAmen.\nJust because I haven\u2019t anything else\nto write about, and because I have a\npressing engagement which will take\nme out of my office, I\u2019m going to in\ntroduce you to \u201cJo Serra,\u201d who makes\na few remarks on general and particu\nlar things:\n\u201cAbout every place I go, people are\nwonderin\u2019 about what is goin\u2019 on with\nbusiness and prices, and they are sorta\nup a tree and confused. And the folks\ndown there on the Potomac, they are\nkinda up to their neck explainin\u2019 why\neverything is not grand and rosy like\nthey said it would be.\n\u201cAnd right along we been told that\nanother law or two would fix every\nthing up sweet and pretty, and the\nrivers would run up hills or sideways\nor whichever way the law says for\n\u2019em to run.\n\u201cBut right recent, everybody seems\nto be sorta gettin\u2019 woke up at about\nthe same time, and we are like Rip\nVan Winkle\u2014the powder was wet and\nhis pants was ragged\u2014and we been\ndreamin,\u2019 but not gettin\u2019 any place.\n\u201cAnd now, if we will take a coupla\nstretches, and a hitch in our belt and\nget over our ideas that somebody is\ngonna feed us, and look after us every\nminute, and we go to work, maybe\nour nap did us some good, after all.\u201d\nAnd he ain\u2019t far wrong, is he?\nWell, Christmas is coming and so\nare taxes and insurance, when Jan\nuary 1 rolls around. There is always\nsomething to take the joy out of life.\nBut, gentle reader, don\u2019t think about\nanything, but buns and bells; cake and\ncandy; turkey and turnips; mint jul\neps and money; and the season will be\nheaven down here below.\nLESSON-SERMON IN\nCHURCHES OF CHRIST\n\u201cGod the Only Cause and Creator\u201d\nwill be the subject of the Lesson-Ser\nmon in all Churches of Christ, Scien\ntist, on Sunday, December 6.\n\"\u201db7\u201d\nFAIR\nWITH YOURSELF\nLet insurance\nSAFEGUARD YOUR\nPROPERTY.\nEdgar Fontaine Agency\nGeneral Insurance-Notary Public\nNo. 207 Peninsula Building\nPhone 177 Office\nResidence 140-W\nThe Golden Text will be from Psa.\n19:1, 3\u2014\u201c The heavens declare the\nglory of God; and the firmament\nshowed his handiwork. There is no\nspeech nor language, where their voice\n1 is not heard.\u201d\nAmong the citations comprising the\nLesson-Sermon will be the following\nfrom the Bibl\u2014Psa. 93:1\u2014\u201cThe Lord\n1 reigneth, he is clothed with majesty;\nthe Lord is clothed with strength,\nJ wherewith he hath girded himself; the\n1 world also is established, that it can\nnot be moved.\u201d\nThe Lesson-Sermon also will include\npassages from the Christian Science\ntextbook, \u201cScience and Health with\nKey to the Scriptures,\u201d by Mary Bak\ner Eddy, among which is the follow\ning, page 503\u2014\u201c God, Spirit, dwelling\nc in infinite light and harmony from\nwhich emanate the true idea, is never\nreflected by aught but the good.\u201d\nServices, Sunday, 11 a. m., Odd Fel\nlows Hall, Pocomoke City.\nSunday, December 6, from 1 to 1:30\nP. M. the Columbia Broadcasting Co.,\nwill radiocast another Christian\nScience program, it may be heard ov\ner Station WCAO, Baltimore, 600 k. c.\nANNUAL PHYSICIAL\nEXAMINATION FOR\nSCHOOL CHILDREN\ni\nHeld Under Joint Auspices Of\nThe State Departments Of\nHealth And Education\nThe annual physicial examination of\nL children in the schools in the Counties\nL by the County Health Officers under\nthe joint auspices of the State Depart\nment of Health and the State Depart\nr ment of Education was started soon\nafter the schools opened for the fall\n1111 umn uuu Hl|j|\nI The alert reader will recognize at once that here\nI is a golden opportunity to obtain the outstanding\nsubscription bargain of the year.\nI THIS NEWSPAPER, lYear\nAnd Any Magazine Listed\u2014Both for Price Shown.\nfl (All subscriptions for one year unless otherwise shown)\nKACAUS n AMERICAN BOY $2.25\nfBSjTJ AMERICAN FRUIT GROWER. 1.75\nAMERICAN MAGAZINE 2.95\nl D >ET HOMB \u2022AIIBWI 2J.\nI pHOVOPIwI HOME 1.75-\nI 1 McCALL\u2019S MAGAZINE ZZZZZ 2.00\nI MODERN MECHANIX 2.25\nn OPEN ROAD (BOYS), 2 YRS 2.00\nI rf||i PAR NTS* MAGAZINE 2.45 I\nI mSm n ropi?iAR L MECHANics\":::z:i\u2014 2.95\nlinni POPULAR SCIENCE MONTHLY.. 2.25\n'bIIIMMII RADIO NEWS SHORT WAVE 2.95\nH REDBOOK MAGAZINE _. 2.95\nI D ROMANTIC MASAZ,NE 2.00\nIK SUCCESSFUL FARMING Z.1ZZ.1.....'. \u00a375\nDESIRED ABOVE (X) I\nI Gentlemen: 1 enclose f. for which send\nI I j me your newspaper for a full year, and the\nWorcester Democrat\nseason. Dental clinics have also been\nresumed.\nIn announcing the arangements for\nthe school year, Dr. R. H. Riley, Di\nrector of the State Department of\nHealth said: \u201cThe plan of concentrat\ning on the children in the lower grades\nwith re-examinations of those in the\nupper grades, was started several\nyears ago, and is being continued in\nthe majority of the schools. In some\nof the smaller schools all of the chil\ndren will be examined. Particular at\ntention is paid to the general health\nand development of the child; symp\ntoms of good or faulty nutrition; to\nthe throat, nose, teeth, condition of\nthe skin, chest conditions, vision, hear\ning and to the child\u2019s posture.\n\u201cThe object of the examinations is\ntwo-fold: First to detect conditions\nthat might lead to illness later on or\nthat might develop into a permanent\nhandicap if allowed to run on. Second\nto bring such conditions to the atten\ntion of the parents, so Chat they may\nbe attended to, promptly.\n\u201cThe younger children are selected\nfor the examinations so that unfavor\nable conditions may be discovered\nwhile they are in the early stages\nwhen they can be corrected most read\nily. Parents are always welcome and\nin some of the schools special arrange\nments are made for them to be pres\nent.\n\u201cLargely through the activities of\nthe parent-teacher associations, and\nthe work of the public health nurses,\nmore interest is taken each year in\nfollowing up the examinations and in\nseeing that conditions in need of cor\nrection, are attended to. The service\nclubs have been a great help, also, in\nproviding the necessary funds for\nglasses and in arranging for other\nspecial services.\n\u201cThe schools are kept under con\nstant supervision to prevent the spread\nof communicable diseases among the\nchildren. Medical inspections of the\nchildren, no matter what grade they\nare in, who have been exposed to scar\nlet fever, diphtheria, measles, whoop\ning cough, or to any of the other di\nseases that are passed readily from\nperson to person, by the health officer\nand the public health nurse of the\ndistrict, constitute a very important\npart of the health department service\nin the schools. Inspections are made,\ndaily, if necessary, when there is dan\nger of an outbreak of any of these\ndiseases.\nREAL ESTATE TRANSFERS\nMarie Anna Shortt from Norman\nj W. Johnson, real estate containing 2\nacres, more or less, near Cedartown,\nj on the West side of the County Road\nleading from Cool Spring to Cedar\ntown. Consideration $lO &c.\ni Sallie Dell, Howard H. Hill, Harry\nP. Dill and Nellie D. Tarpay from\nJohn L. Sanford, Jr., and wife, 2 par\ncels of real estate in Berlin in the\nt 9th Elec. Dist., one on the Easterly\nside of West Street and the other on\nthe Southeast side of West Street.\nConsideration $lO &c.\nSidney L. Cropper and Estella A.\nCropper, his wife, from John W. Mum\ni ford and wife, the \u201cGilly Bradford\nPlace,\u201d containing 60 acres, more or\nless in the 4th Elec. Dist. Considera\ntion $lO &c.\nI John H. Gillis and Mary A. F. Gil\nlis from John L. Sanford, Jr., and\nWm. G. Kerbin, Jr., Trustees and oth- i\ners, real estate containing 3.19 acres,\nmore or less in the 9th Elec. Dist., on\nthe Southwest side of the State Stone\nRoad leading from Berlin to Salisbury.\ni Consideration $2Ol &c.\nCARD OF THANKS\nWe wish to express our appreciation\nto all who assisted in any way during\nthe illness and at the funeral of our\ns mother, Mrs. Amanda E. Stevens,\nj Her children\nDec. 3-ltp.\n\ni CARD OF THANKS\nt\nWe take this method of showing our\ndeep appreciation for the many kind\nt nesses shown us during the illness\nand death of our wife and mother,\nt Mrs. Burley Phillips. Also for the\nbeautiful floral tributes and use of\ncars.\nMr. Burley Phillips and children\nj Dec. 3-lt.\nh\nL. Paul Ewell, Attorney at Law\nSheriff\u2019s Sale\nOF VALUABLE\nTract of Land on\nthe road to Virginia\nUnder and by virtue of a writ of\nfieri facias issued out of the Circuit\nCourt for Worcester County, Mary\nland, at the suit of Young Son, In\ni corporated, against Clarence Phillips\nand Virginia Phillips, and to me di\nrected, I have seized, levied upon and\ntaken in execution all the right, title,\ninterest and estate of the said Clar\nence Phillips and Virginia Phillips,\nhis wife, in and to the following real\nestate: All that tract or parcel of land\nsituate on the northeast side of the\nState stone road leading from Poco\nmoke City to Virginia, having a width\nof one hundred yards on the State\nstone road, and a depth of four hun\ndred yards, thus containing about 7%\nacres, and being all and the same tract\nor parcel of land granted and con\nveyed to the said Clarence Phillips as\nClarence F. Phillips, by J. Frank\nPhillips and others by deed dated Sep\ntember 28, 1928, and recorded among\nthe land records of Worcester County,\nMaryland, in Liber B. B. No. 6, folios\n159, etc.\nAnd I hereby give notice that on\nSaturday, Dec. 18,1937\nAt the hour of 9:30 o\u2019clock A. M.,\non the premises, in the First Election\nDistrict of Worcester County, Mary\nland, I will offer for sale at public\nauction to the highest bidder for cash,\nall the right, title, interest and estate\nof the said Clarence Phillips and Vir\nginia Phillips in and to the foregoing\nreal estate to satisfy said writ with\ncosts and costs of sale.\nERNEST C. WEST,\nSheriff of Worcester County.\nCLAIBORNE ANNAPOLIS\nMATAPEAKE FERRIES\nSave 100 Miles\nFALL SCHEDULE\nEffective September 28th, 1937\nDAILY SUNDAY (E. S. T.)\nBetween Annapolis and Matapeake\nLEAVE LEAVE\nANNAPOLIS MATAPEAKE\n8:00 a. m. 7:25 a. m\n10:00 a. m. 9:00 a. m\n11:00 a. m. 11:00 a. m\n12:00 noon 12:00 noon\n1:00 p. m. 1:00 p. m.\n2:00 p. m. 2:00 p. m\n3:00 p. m. 3:00 p. m.\n4:00 p. m. 4:00 p. m\n6:00 p. m. 5:00 p. m\n8:00 p. m. 7:00 p. m\nBetween Annapolis and Claiborne\nLEAVE LEAVE\nANNAPOLIS CLAIBORNE\n7:30 a. m. 9:30 a. m\n5:00 p. m. 7:00 p. m\nThe Claiborne-Anoapolis Ferry Co.\nANNAPOLIS. MD.\nODD COLDS\nDD 0 fever\nLiquid, Tablets first day on\nSalve, Nose Headache, 30\nDrops minutes\nTry \u201cRub-My-Tism\u201d World\u2019s Best\nLiniment\nDR. R. I. GIVENS\nDENTIST\nOffice over New Callahan\nBuilding\nPhone\u20143l3\nFriday, DeJTmber 3, 193 T\nClassified Advertising\nAll Classified Advertising is charg\ned at 2 cents per word. Cash or\nstamps must accompany all orders.\nNo ad taken for less than 25 cents.\nCHURCH NOTICES\nTURKEY DINNER\u2014With all the\n\u201cfixins\u201d and dessert. Bethany M. P.\nSocial Hall, Thursday evening, De\ncember 9th.\nDec. 3-lt.\nThe Ladies of the Baptist Church\nof Parksley, Virginia will serve their\nannual chicken salad and oyster sup\nper, December 10, in Johnson\u2019s Hall,\nbeginning at 4P. M. Price 35 cents.\nWe take this method of inviting our\nneighbor friends of Pocomoke to come\nand eat with us, and enjoy this festive\nseason.\nDec. 3-2 t.\nWANTED\nWORK WANTED Stenographic\nor Bookkeeping. Doris Clapham.\nDec. 3-2tp.\nMAN WANTED\u2014To supply Raw\nleigh\u2019s Household Products to nearby\nconsumers. Sales way up this year.\nWe train and help you. Good profits\nfor hustlers. No experience necessary.\nPleasant, profitable, dignified work.\nWrite today. Rawleigh\u2019s, Dept. MDL\n-98-53, Chester, Pa.\nDec. 3-ltp.\nWANTED Reliable tenant for\ngood farm; large dwelling, new bam.\nLiberal terms and extended lease to\nright man. Samuel F. Miles, Prin\ncess Anne, Md. Phone 11F11.\nNov. 26-3tp.\nFOR SALE\nFOR SALE\u2014Apple sauce made\ncakes, in 60 cents or SI.OO size. Mrs.\nLuther Parsons, Phone 5 F 12.\nFOR SALE\u2014Bucket a day coal\nwater heater. Merrill\u2019s garage.\nNov. 26-tf.\nFOR SALE\u2014Pierce Arrow car and\nBaysinger Trailer, ready for a Florida\ntrip. Cheap. Apply Howard Philips,\nGeorgetown, Delaware.\nNov. 19-3 t.\nFOR SALE\u2014We have received an\nother lot of approximately 3100 gal\nlons of paint. Prices ranging from\neighty-five cents (.85) per gallon oa\nup. Layton Layton, Inc., George\ntown, Delaware.\nNov. 19-3 t.\nFOR SALE\u2014Dining room suite,\nbedroom suite, feather bed, large size\nbeveled edge mirror. Arthur M. Mc-\nDaniel.\nNov. 12-4tp.\nFOR SALE\u2014A large assortment ef\nused Oil and Gasoline Stoves at bar\ngain prices. Eastern Shore Gas Co.,\nPocomoke 12-2-tf.\nFOR RENT\nFOR RENT\u2014First floor \u201cHolland\nApartment,\u201d cor. Second and Maple\nSts. W. H. Clarke.\nDec. 3-tf.\nTWO APARTMENTS FOR RENT\n-509 Walnut St. Possession Dec. 29.\nApply M. William Miller, phone 385.\nDec. 3-tf.\n3-ROOM APARTMENT FOR RENT\nLights and bath\u20144os Laurel St.\nNov. 12-tf\nFOR RENT\u2014S-room house with\nmodem conveniences and garage. Ap\nply to 704 Second St.\nNov. 12-tf.\nFOR RENT\u2014Modem 4-room apart\nment with lights and bath. Dr. N. B.\nSartorius.\nNov 5-tf.\nAPARTMENT FOR RENT\u2014Apply\nAllen D. Merrill Bros.\nOct. 22-tf.\n5-ROOM APARTMENT FOR RENT\nLights and bath. Henrietta Chatham.\nSept. 24-tf.\nAPARTMENT FOR RENT\u2014Fur\nnished or unfurnished. 105 Laurel St.\nSept. 24-tf.\nLOST\nLOST\u2014White tom cat, three gray\nspots, ring tail. Information as to\nwhereabouts appreciated. WAR\nWICK\u2019S, Dunn Swamp Road.\nDec. 3-ltp.\nLOST \u2014A double barrel gun some\nwhere on road from my home to\nDouble Bridges. Reward. J. P. Gootee\nDec. 3-ltp.\nMISCELLANEOUS\nWHY NOT A SPENCER FOR A\nCHRISTMAS GlFT?\u2014Spencer Foun\ndation Garments are most acceptable\nto mother, wife or daughter. See\nMrs. W. B. Rock.\nNov. 26-3 t.\nSEWING\u2014DoIIs. wardrobes,. etc.\nReasonable. 701 Walnut St., phone\n297-W.\nNov. 19-3 t.\nDR. G. E. FlNNEY\u2014Graduate Lic\nensed Veterinarian. Onancock, Va.\nPhone 168. Aug.-27-tf\nFeet Hurt? Groh\u2019s Sponge Rubber\nArch Supports relieves tired aching\ncalloused feet. For comfort Phone\n128 W or write, Mr. Groh.\nMarch 19-tf.\nNOTICE\u2014Price on hair cutting\u2014\n-25 cents will remain the same at\n\u25a0'haws.\nJuly 10-tf","height":"23238","width":"19620"}}
